        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date when="1914-12-28">December 28, 1914.</date>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>My dear <persName key="margaret_anderson">Miss Anderson</persName>:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I am returning  the galley-proof of <title key="allies" level="a">“The Allies,”</title> which has just this minute come.
                    There are the usual mistakes the printers always make with that
                    <del rend="strikethrough">meter</del><add place="above" type="insertion" rend="pencil">metre</add>, 
                    which is unpardonable considering the way the typewritten manuscript is written, but never mind! They
                    have left out all the stanza spaces. This I have indicated, and will you kindly see on the other
                    proofs that they <del rend="strikethrough">come in</del><add place="above" type="insertion" rend="pencil">are done</add> correctly? 
                    Read without stanzas, this <rs key="polyProse" type="style">polyphonic prose</rs> becomes almost unintelligible, and the refrain is lost.</p>
                <p>The other mistakes are: one broken type, <hi rend="quoted">“blinds”</hi> for <hi rend="quoted">“binds”</hi> in the second line, and the
                    last word, <hi rend="quoted">“Peace,”</hi> should go along towards the middle of the line. But above all, please be
                    careful about those stanza spaces. I always have the same trouble with <persName key="harriet_monroe">Harriet Monroe</persName>'s printer
                    whenever he prints this polyphonic prose.</p>
                <p><gap><desc>There are words cut off here</desc></gap>reat haste,</p>
                    <closer>Very sincerely yours,</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
